The start symbol S has only three productions:

1. S → NT142 NT94  
2. S → NT24 NT102  
3. S → NT144 NT80  

So the first terminal of any sentence in the language must come from the left–hand non-terminal of one of those three alternatives.

• NT24 can only produce the single terminal t14.  
• NT144 can only produce the single terminal t58.  
• NT142 can produce
  – the single terminal t2, or  
  – a string beginning with t44 (via NT136), or  
  – a string beginning with t13 (via NT198).  

None of these possibilities begins with t53, yet the string we are given starts with t53.

Since no derivation from S can yield a sentence whose first symbol is t53, the provided string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only start-production that can match the first token t44 is

S → NT142 NT94  
NT142 → NT136 NT70       (NT136 → 't44')

so the derivation must begin with the sequence  

t44 … = NT136 NT70 …

NT70 has the unique expansion NT70 → NT134 NT94 with NT134 → 't16', forcing  

t44 t16 … = NT136 NT134 NT94 …

Hence the third token (start of the inner NT94) must be produced by NT94.

NT94 has only two binary rules:

1. NT94 → NT148 NT151   (first token produced is t53)
2. NT94 → NT211 NT52    (first token produced is either t18 or t69)

Our string’s third token is t53, so rule 1 must be chosen:

NT94 → NT148 NT151 with NT148 → 't53'

But NT151 → NT209 NT125 and NT125 → 't0', which means every derivation using rule 1 necessarily ends with the terminal t0. Consequently the inner NT94 would have to place the unique token t0 somewhere before the final position of the whole string, leaving further symbols to be produced afterwards— impossible, because t0 is the last symbol of the given string.

Therefore no derivation starting from S can match the required prefix, and the string cannot be generated by the grammar.

Answer: No

To be in the language the sentential form produced by the start symbol S must match one of the three CNF alternatives

  1) S → NT142 NT94  
  2) S → NT24  NT102  
  3) S → NT144 NT80

The given 41-token string begins with t58 and ends with t8.

1)  For S → NT24 NT102 the first token generated must be the only terminal NT24 can yield, namely t14.  
    The string begins with t58, therefore this alternative is impossible.

2)  For S → NT142 NT94 the final token of the whole string is produced by NT94 (because NT142’s yield precedes NT94’s).  
    The only ways NT94 can expand are  

        NT94 → NT211 NT52  
        NT94 → NT148 NT151  

    The right-most terminals these productions can ultimately generate are

        – t7  (via NT52 → NT162 NT143, NT143 → t7)  
        – t5  (via NT52 → NT79 NT85, NT85 → t5)  
        – t33 (via NT52 → t33)  
        – t0  (via NT151 → NT209 NT125, NT125 → t0)

    None of those terminals equals the required final token t8, so alternative (1) is impossible.

3)  For S → NT144 NT80 we must have

        NT144 ⇒ t58                (only possible expansion of NT144)
        NT80  ⇒ … t8               (NT80 must cover the remaining 40 tokens and end with t8)

    NT80 can only expand as NT80 → NT165 NT72 with NT72 ⇒ t8, so NT165 has to
    cover the 39 tokens preceding t8 and end with the token t5 (the 40th token).

        NT165 can expand either as  
            a) NT165 ⇒ t20                         (ends with t20, not t5) or  
            b) NT165 ⇒ NT78 NT150

        Hence option (b) is forced.  
        NT150 must then account for the final token t5 inside NT165’s yield.

            NT150’s possibilities:  
                – NT150 ⇒ t56                     (ends with t56, not t5)  
                – NT150 ⇒ NT175 NT85  with NT85 ⇒ t5

            So we must have NT150 ⇒ NT175 NT85 and thus NT175 has to generate
            the 38 tokens that precede the concluding t5.

            But NT175 has exactly one rule: NT175 ⇒ NT70 NT58.
            Therefore its yield ends with whatever NT58 ends with.
            NT58 can end only with t63, t7 or t16 (proof analogous to the
            analysis for NT94), never with the required terminal t42,
            which actually is the penultimate token of the string.

    Consequently alternative (3) is also impossible.

Since none of the three possible derivations from S can match the required first or last tokens of the given string, the string is not generated by the grammar.

No
